Featured List, News - Financial Planning, News - Investment, News - Superannuation
Mercer to launch retirement game changer





30-Oct-2014
By Kristen Crawford 

















Related Articles: Market flexibility key to enhancing super |  | 


Mercer has announced the launch of an innovative investment option expected to provide a solution to weaknesses in Australia’s current retirement income system.

According to Mercer’s latest research, 54 per cent of Australians expected to have less money than they needed for the lifestyle they desired in retirement, while one in four Australians would outlive their retirement savings by more than 10 years. 

Yesterday, Media Super and VicSuper were revealed as the first two industry funds set to take on Mercer’s new longevity solution product, LifetimePlus, early next quarter.

The company said its investment option was the world’s first pooled mortality investment fund, designed to protect more Australians against the risk of outliving their savings.

Mercer managing director and Pacific market leader David Anderson said retirement would be a financial challenge for many. 

“Life might be simple but comfortable for the first decade or so, but once savings run out the age pension will only provide about half the amount required for a ‘comfortable lifestyle’, according to ASFA (Association of Superannuation Funds of Australia),” Anderson said.

VicSuper chief executive Michael Dundon said he was impressed to witness such an innovative product development happening in the retirement income space.

“To ensure our members can maintain their desired lifestyles in retirement, we believe we must provide appropriate solutions which manage the risks they face, as well as providing for their income needs,” Dundon said.

“An adviser-led, income-layering approach to building a member’s retirement portfolio can provide the best outcome for our members.

“Using an innovative product suite is fundamental to this approach.” 

LifetimePlus is expected to be primarily delivered to consumers via financial advisers, since circumstances upon entering the longevity investment, including a member’s age and superannuation account balance, will directly determine the product’s suitability, effectiveness and productivity of their returns.

Mercer senior partner and senior actuary David Knox said the investor must have a retirement pension in order to enter the shared pooled investment.

Knox explained that what differentiated the option from others was that it was deliberately biased towards those who lived longest in order to give those members the sustained confidence that they would have enough savings to maintain their lifestyle until they died.

Apart from assessing the suitability of the product for each investor on a case-by-case basis, advisers will also be responsible for delivering imperative product information to members.  

Anderson said despite LifetimePlus initially only being delivered by financial planners, it could be expected to evolve over time, become a retail fund and eventually have the potential to be made directly available to consumers. 


